To implement a simplified version of Git called `minigit` in Perl, we will create a script that handles basic version control functionalities. Below is a basic outline of how to implement this, including the necessary Perl code and instructions for making the script executable.

### Step 1: Create the `minigit` Perl Script

Create a file named `minigit` and add the following Perl code to it. This code will handle basic commands like `init`, `add`, `commit`, and `status`.

```perl
#!/usr/bin/perl
use strict;
use warnings;
use File::Path qw(make_path);
use File::Basename;

my $repo_dir = ".minigit";

sub init {
    unless (-d $repo_dir) {
        make_path($repo_dir);
        print "Initialized empty minigit repository in $repo_dir\n";
    } else {
        print "Repository already exists in $repo_dir\n";
    }
}

sub add {
    my @files = @_;
    my $index_file = "$repo_dir/index";

    open my $fh, '>>', $index_file or die "Could not open index file: $!";
    foreach my $file (@files) {
        if (-e $file) {
            print $fh "$file\n";
            print "Added $file to index\n";
        } else {
            print "File $file does not exist\n";
        }
    }
    close $fh;
}

sub commit {
    my $message = shift;
    my $index_file = "$repo_dir/index";

    unless (-e $index_file) {
        print "No files added to commit. Use 'minigit add <file>' first.\n";
        return;
    }

    my $commit_dir = "$repo_dir/commits";
    make_path($commit_dir);

    my $commit_file = "$commit_dir/commit_" . time() . ".txt";
    open my $fh, '>', $commit_file or die "Could not open commit file: $!";
    print $fh "Commit message: $message\n";
    print $fh "Files:\n";
    open my $index_fh, '<', $index_file or die "Could not open index file: $!";
    while (my $line = <$index_fh>) {
        print $fh "$line";
    }
    close $index_fh;
    close $fh;

    print "Committed changes with message: '$message'\n";
    unlink $index_file;  # Clear index after commit
}

sub status {
    my $index_file = "$repo_dir/index";
    if (-e $index_file) {
        print "Changes to be committed:\n";
        open my $fh, '<', $index_file or die "Could not open index file: $!";
        while (my $line = <$fh>) {
            print "  $line";
        }
        close $fh;
    } else {
        print "No changes to commit.\n";
    }
}

# Main command handling
my $command = shift @ARGV;

if ($command eq 'init') {
    init();
} elsif ($command eq 'add') {
    add(@ARGV);
} elsif ($command eq 'commit') {
    commit(shift @ARGV);
} elsif ($command eq 'status') {
    status();
} else {
    print "Usage: ./minigit <command> [<args>]\n";
    print "Commands:\n";
    print "  init\n";
    print "  add <file>\n";
    print "  commit <message>\n";
    print "  status\n";
}
```

### Step 2: Make the Script Executable

After creating the `minigit` file, you need to make it executable. You can do this by running the following command in your terminal:

```bash
chmod +x minigit
```

### Step 3: Create a Test Script

You mentioned running `bash test-v1.sh`. Ensure you have a test script named `test-v1.sh` that contains the necessary tests for your `minigit` implementation. Here is a simple example of what that might look like:

```bash
#!/bin/bash

# Test minigit initialization
./minigit init
# Test adding a file
echo "Hello, World!" > testfile.txt
./minigit add testfile.txt
# Test status
./minigit status
# Test commit
./minigit commit "Initial commit"
# Test status after commit
./minigit status
# Clean up
rm -rf .minigit
rm testfile.txt
```

Make this script executable as well:

```bash
chmod +x test-v1.sh
```

### Step 4: Run the Tests

Finally, run the test script to verify your implementation:

```bash
bash test-v1.sh
```

### Conclusion

This implementation of `minigit` in Perl provides basic functionality for initializing a repository, adding files, committing changes, and checking the status. You can expand upon this by adding more features as needed.
